2026-01-26T18:44:17.356131Z  INFO codex_core::stream_events_utils: ToolCall: shell_command {"command":"cat <<'EOF' > /Users/duhl/git/anedot-frontend/LEAD_PAGES_EXTRACTION_PLAN.md\n# Lead Pages Extraction Plan\n\n## Why this is a good idea\n- Clear domain boundary: Lead pages are a distinct “collect intent” flow versus donation/storefront. The code already gates behavior by `pageType === 'lead'`, which indicates a separable domain surface.\n- Faster iteration: Isolating lead-page UI + workflows reduces coupling to donation logic (payments, receipts, compliance), which can speed feature delivery and reduce regression risk.\n- Smaller bundle / clearer ownership: Leads are lighter-weight pages; splitting them can reduce frontend bundle weight and enable a team to own a smaller, focused surface.\n- Reduced cognitive load: Developers no longer need to reason about donation/storefront logic when touching lead pages.\n- Future flexibility: A separate app can evolve toward a lightweight public landing page system or be embedded externally, without dragging donation features.\n\n## 1) Scope Definition\n\n### In-scope for new repo (Lead Pages app)\n- Lead page builder UX (page creation/editing, form fields, layout, preview).\n- Lead page public view (submission flow, validation, success UX, analytics).\n- Lead-specific workflows (email receipt/confirmations, recover/retry).\n- Lead-specific translations, schemas, analytics events.\n\n### Out-of-scope (stays in monolith repo for now)\n- Donation/storefront/event page types.\n- Payment processing, fees, installments, express checkout.\n- Any organization admin features not strictly lead-specific.\n\n### Decisions to make early\n- Is the new app a standalone frontend that consumes existing backend APIs?\n- Do we keep a shared backend (Rails/API) or spin out a lead-specific service?\n- How to authenticate builder access (SSO, token exchange)?\n\n## 2) Architecture Options\n\n### Option A: Frontend-only split (recommended first step)\n- Create a new frontend repo for lead pages.\n- Continue to use existing backend APIs.\n- Keep data model as-is initially; only separate frontend ownership.\n\n### Option B: Full service split\n- New frontend repo + new backend service for lead pages.\n- Requires data migration and API re-implementation.\n\nGiven the request includes data migration, this plan assumes Option B is the long-term target, with a phased migration starting with Option A.\n\n## 3) Phased Plan\n\n### Phase 0 — Discovery & Alignment\n- Inventory all lead page logic in current repo:\n  - Builder UI, public view, analytics, workflow definitions.\n  - Shared components that are used by non-lead pages.\n- Identify all backend endpoints and models used by lead pages.\n- Define ownership (team, release cadence, ops).\n\n**Deliverable**: Lead Pages scope map + list of API dependencies.\n\n### Phase 1 — New Repository Setup\n- Create new repo (e.g., `lead-pages-frontend`).\n- Set up build tooling, linting, CI, environments, and config.\n- Extract lead-page-only code:\n  - `src/pages/ActionPages/pages/ActionPagesBuilder/` (lead-only pieces)\n  - `src/pages/ActionPages/pages/PublicActionPage/ActionPageView/` (lead-only flows)\n  - Shared UI components needed by lead pages.\n- Replace internal routing with a minimal lead-pages routing table.\n\n**Deliverable**: Lead pages app builds and runs with mocked APIs.\n\n### Phase 2 — API Integration (no data migration yet)\n- Integrate against existing APIs with a stable interface.\n- Create a compatibility layer for any shared types/schemas.\n- Validate analytics events (lead-specific vs donation).\n\n**Deliverable**: Lead pages app powered by existing data.\n\n### Phase 3 — Data Migration Plan & Backend Split (long-term)\n\nThis is the data migration strategy for lead-specific data. The goal is to move lead pages into their own service without breaking existing pages.\n\n#### 3.1 Data Model Inventory\nIdentify “lead-specific” and “shared” data.\n\n**Likely lead-specific**\n- Lead page definitions (page type = lead)\n- Lead page form fields schema\n- Lead submissions (form responses)\n- Lead-specific workflows (email templates, confirmation screen, recover logic)\n\n**Likely shared / cross-cutting**\n- Organization/account ownership\n- Users and auth\n- Assets (images, logos)\n- Generic “page” metadata (title, slug, vanity URLs)\n\n#### 3.2 Target Model in Lead Service\nDesign new service schema:\n- `lead_pages`\n- `lead_page_fields`\n- `lead_submissions`\n- `lead_workflows`\n- `lead_page_assets` (if not shared)\n\nAdd org/account references (foreign keys or external IDs).\n\n#### 3.3 Migration Strategy (Phased, Dual-Write)\n1) Read-only snapshot\n   - Extract existing lead data to a staging export.\n   - Validate completeness and uniqueness (e.g., slug collisions).\n2) Backfill into new service\n   - Import pages, fields, submissions, workflows.\n   - Generate deterministic IDs or map old IDs → new IDs.\n3) Dual-write window\n   - When lead page edits happen in monolith, write to both systems.\n   - Lead submissions get written to both systems.\n4) Read switch\n   - Public lead pages read from new service.\n   - Builder reads from new service.\n5) Decommission\n   - Stop dual writes.\n   - Archive legacy lead data in monolith.\n\n#### 3.4 Migration Mapping & ID Strategy\n- Create an ID mapping table (legacy_id → new_id).\n- Preserve:\n  - `slug` values\n  - `organization_id` references\n  - submission metadata (timestamps, IP, UTM fields)\n- Ensure public URLs remain unchanged.\n\n#### 3.5 Data Quality Validation\n- Compare counts per org: pages, submissions, fields.\n- Random sampling of page rendering consistency.\n- Validate submission exports match.\n\n## 4) Cutover Strategy\n\n- Soft launch: route a subset of lead pages to the new app.\n- Feature flag: per-org or per-page routing.\n- Rollback: reverse routing if issues appear.\n\n## 5) Risks & Mitigations\n\n- Shared component drift → Create a shared UI package or copy only stable components.\n- API coupling → Define a stable lead-specific API contract early.\n- Slug collisions or URL changes → Preserve slug/URL mapping and verify on import.\n- Data loss → Dual-write with full audit logs; compare record counts.\n\n## 6) Deliverables Checklist\n\n- Lead pages repo with build + CI\n- API compatibility layer\n- Data migration scripts + mapping tables\n- Dual-write implementation\n- Cutover and rollback plan\n- Post-migration cleanup PRs\n\n## Open Questions (need your input)\n\n1) Should this be frontend-only first, or full backend split from day one?\n2) Who owns the lead page backend today, and can we add endpoints or a new service?\n3) How strict is URL preservation? Are vanity domains in play?\n4) Do we need to migrate historical submissions, or only active ones?\nEOF","workdir":"/Users/duhl/git/anedot-frontend"}
